&gt;&gt; CeCe Conway: In 1933 John Lomax

00:06:55.140 --> 00:06:58.270
and 18 year old Alan
began collecting folksongs

00:06:58.270 --> 00:06:59.570
for the Library of Congress.

00:06:59.570 --> 00:07:05.050
A little later John was named the
honorary consultant and curator

00:07:05.050 --> 00:07:09.650
of the archived American folksong,
and he and Teddy Roosevelt used

00:07:09.650 --> 00:07:12.630
to meet together to
discuss what kind

00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:18.490
of folklore would be appropriate
to link to our wonderful lands,

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:21.700
and they picked the cowboy.

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:26.130
Now, this is Hobart Smith
who's one of the early people

00:07:26.130 --> 00:07:30.760
that they recorded playing
"Banging Breakdown".

00:07:30.760 --> 00:07:35.800
And you'll notice that banjo,
it's what we call a mountain banjo

00:07:35.800 --> 00:07:41.980
and that's an inset rim and
it arrived near where I teach

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:48.170
in the northwestern mountains
just after the Civil War.

00:07:48.170 --> 00:07:54.920
One of the ancestral folks
stopped off there in Wilkesboro,

00:07:54.920 --> 00:07:59.830
sometimes considered the
moonshining capital of the world,

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:04.580
and brought back a pattern for the
first banjo that was made there.

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:08.990
And now these banjos are made
within about a hundred miles only,

00:08:08.990 --> 00:08:11.950
apparently, of where
Virginia, North Carolina

00:08:11.950 --> 00:08:17.850
and Tennessee come together.

00:08:17.850 --> 00:08:21.510
That was Hobart Smith
from Saltville.

00:08:21.510 --> 00:08:27.040
So here's Alan, young Alan, who
became the assistant in charge,

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:30.510
and he remained there until 1942.

00:08:30.510 --> 00:08:39.040
[ Music ]

00:08:39.040 --> 00:08:42.290
He and his father, and
also his sister Bess,

00:08:42.290 --> 00:08:43.970
recorded all over the south.

00:08:43.970 --> 00:08:49.360
And Bess was a fantastic folklorist
who became the head of the NEA

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:54.620
and the traditional arts and
instituted the National Endowment

00:08:54.620 --> 00:08:58.420
for the Arts Fellowship Heritage
Awards that are being given

00:08:58.420 --> 00:09:02.130
in this building tonight, actually.

00:09:04.260 --> 00:09:09.100
She also is, as far as I know, the
first folklorist who put the name

00:09:09.100 --> 00:09:12.170
of her coworker, Bessie Jones

00:09:12.170 --> 00:09:14.970
from the Sea Islands,
on the book with her.

00:09:14.970 --> 00:09:20.340
She and Bessie together
were credited with writing

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:22.650
that book, which was wonderful.

00:09:22.650 --> 00:09:27.400
Alan also got to go on a trip
led by Zora Neale Hurston.

00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:31.910
She took them to and Mary
Elizabeth Barnicle went, too,

00:09:31.910 --> 00:09:35.020
and they went to the Georgia Sea
Islands and then to Eatonville,

00:09:35.020 --> 00:09:40.910
Florida, and then Alan
and Miss Barnicle would go

00:09:40.910 --> 00:09:44.510
on to Nassau and the Bahamas.

00:09:44.510 --> 00:09:57.060
[ Music ]

00:09:57.060 --> 00:10:02.370
When Alan left the Library
of Congress in 1942,

00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:05.890
for some months he
wrote back to the man

00:10:05.890 --> 00:10:09.080
in charge telling him
things he needed to do,

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:13.480
and that was really wonderful
because Alan had been so busy doing

00:10:13.480 --> 00:10:16.450
so many things while he was
here, he never wrote them down,

00:10:16.450 --> 00:10:20.220
and there were many things
we never found out about.

00:10:20.220 --> 00:10:24.870
And one of the ones that was
especially interesting was a letter

00:10:24.870 --> 00:10:28.260
talking about Pete Steele,
a wonderful banjo player,

00:10:28.260 --> 00:10:34.070
and he said to the acting person,
get that check off to Pete Steele,

00:10:34.070 --> 00:10:40.420
his wife's sick, I think she has
cancer, they need the $12.43 now.

00:10:41.450 --> 00:10:45.690
So that was the sort of many
things he was doing daily.

00:10:47.710 --> 00:10:52.440
Something else that Alan and his
father did that was really exciting

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:56.390
in their work was find
very ancient instruments,

00:10:56.390 --> 00:10:59.250
and these were the quills.

00:10:59.250 --> 00:11:03.660
They had appeared played by Henry
Thomas, [inaudible] from Texas

00:11:03.660 --> 00:11:09.530
who had made an earlier recording,
and along with the whoops

00:11:09.530 --> 00:11:11.510
as well, that's part of it.

00:11:11.510 --> 00:11:39.200
[ Music ]

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:46.670
And the Harry Thomas
quill playing was included

00:11:46.670 --> 00:11:51.340
in Harry Smith's anthology
of folksong,

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:54.930
which brought out a whole bunch
of 78s on long play records

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:56.790
and became kind of the bible

00:11:56.790 --> 00:12:01.600
for the folk festival
revival of the '50s and '60s.

00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:07.500
But it was interesting that
Alan had met these musicians

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:12.790
after he had worked with John
C. Work at Fisk University,

00:12:12.790 --> 00:12:19.980 position:56%
and the paying flute player gave him
a tip about finding Sid Hemphill.

00:12:19.980 --> 00:12:30.500
And here we've got him imitating
the dog chasing the fox.

00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:33.170
So Sid also played the fiddle.

00:12:33.170 --> 00:12:40.870
And Alan went to Scotland and
England and Ireland and Spain

00:12:40.870 --> 00:12:47.340
and Italy and collected from
1951 to '59, I believe it was,

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:51.610
and he did that partly because
he had great opportunities there.

00:12:51.610 --> 00:12:56.650
He had been working with the BBC
in putting out records and getting

00:12:56.650 --> 00:12:58.350
to work with really good equipment.

00:12:58.350 --> 00:13:01.760
And while he was there not only
did he collect hours and hours,

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:04.020
I was staggered with
how much there was,

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:09.670 position:56%
but he also produced radio shows
and five albums for the world music.

00:13:09.670 --> 00:13:14.000
And so this was helping the people

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.270
who played this wonderful
music be more appreciated

00:13:17.270 --> 00:13:23.630
and get more recognition, including
the kinkers, the travellers

00:13:23.630 --> 00:13:26.400
who lived near around Aberdeenshire

00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:29.190
and had been dismissed
by many people.

00:13:29.190 --> 00:13:37.920
And eventually Jeannie Robertson
received the British Empire Medal

00:13:37.920 --> 00:13:42.470
of Honor from the Queen and
she was the first folk singer

00:13:42.470 --> 00:13:45.680
and the first traveller to ever
get that award in the '50s.

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:49.190
