00:20:13.510 --> 00:20:25.070
[ Music ]

00:20:25.070 --> 00:20:28.830
Oh, now, here we've got one
of these double items again.

00:20:28.830 --> 00:20:34.440
But Alan did a movie
in Williamsburg.

00:20:34.440 --> 00:20:38.850 position:56%
He took musicians to the Sea Islands
to rehearse for two or three days,

00:20:38.850 --> 00:20:41.290
and they had never met each other,

00:20:41.290 --> 00:20:45.120
and they were so good they
were able to play together.

00:20:45.120 --> 00:20:52.060
And the idea of the movie
was that it was supposed

00:20:52.060 --> 00:20:56.300
to show late 18th century
music in Williamsburg.

00:20:56.300 --> 00:21:02.710
And he took two traditions that
had not really intermingled

00:21:02.710 --> 00:21:06.400
at that time; one from the
upper south, the banjo,

00:21:06.400 --> 00:21:09.710
fiddle string tradition,
influenced particularly

00:21:09.710 --> 00:21:19.470
by African American players,
and by Scot-Irish fiddlers

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:29.650 position:56%
and then he took the Deep South
tradition which had a lot of singing

00:21:29.650 --> 00:21:36.100
and different styles of music,
like the southeast Sea Islands,

00:21:36.100 --> 00:21:39.450
and then they intermixed
all of that in this movie.

00:21:39.450 --> 00:21:42.860
So it maybe never really
happened all at one time,

00:21:42.860 --> 00:21:45.260
but it was artistically
very creative.

00:21:45.260 --> 00:21:55.180
And it was also interesting
because after he left for Scotland

00:21:55.180 --> 00:22:00.770
and Europe, in 1952 Harry
Smith put out his anthology,

00:22:00.770 --> 00:22:06.620
and I believe that was the first
released record set that had blacks

00:22:06.620 --> 00:22:11.190
and whites intermingled
on the records themselves.

00:22:11.190 --> 00:22:13.880
And because the record companies,

00:22:13.880 --> 00:22:17.700
the 78 record companies
