00:27:00.350 --> 00:27:04.440 position:56%
that he could play old time music,
too, and really encouraged him to do

00:27:04.440 --> 00:27:07.060
that and recorded him and
brought him a lot of places,

00:27:07.060 --> 00:27:09.590
like up here to the
Smithsonian Folk Festival.

00:27:09.590 --> 00:27:16.620
And when Ralph died,
on NPR Doc said,

00:27:16.620 --> 00:27:23.990
He left me better than he found me.

00:27:23.990 --> 00:27:32.510 position:56%
When I wrote my book, we thought
that the ngoni and the Wolff, Holum,

00:27:32.510 --> 00:27:37.000
[phonetic], the semi spike griot
lutes were the primary ancestor

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:40.190
of our American banjo in the south.

00:27:40.190 --> 00:27:45.640
And partly we thought this
was because of Paul Oliver

00:27:45.640 --> 00:27:48.900
who had written a wonderful
book, a British man,

00:27:48.900 --> 00:27:54.890
on the Savannah Syncopaters and he
had heard the musical similarities

00:27:54.890 --> 00:27:59.020
between those players and the blues
and really didn't know as much

00:27:59.020 --> 00:28:03.480
about banjo tradition
as we know now.

00:28:03.480 --> 00:28:09.760
But we were wrong then and
new evidence has come I mean,

00:28:09.760 --> 00:28:13.150
those instruments were
eventually very important,

00:28:13.150 --> 00:28:18.860
I think particularly influencing
fingerpicking style, but again,

00:28:18.860 --> 00:28:24.180
it has not always been so that the
White Mountain musician was the

00:28:24.180 --> 00:28:29.000
symbol of the banjo because it was
brought here by Africans no later

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:33.030
than 1740 into Maryland
and the South,

00:28:33.030 --> 00:28:37.940
and for a hundred years they were
about the only ones who played it.

00:28:37.940 --> 00:28:43.940
They came from southern Gambia,
below the Casamance River.

00:28:43.940 --> 00:28:45.980
The Jola people lived there.

00:28:45.980 --> 00:28:51.940
And a fellow named Daniel Jatta was
in this country getting his M B.A.

00:28:51.940 --> 00:28:58.820
and he began to hear
about the banjo.

00:28:58.820 --> 00:29:05.220
So here you can see southern
Gambian and the Casamance River,

00:29:05.220 --> 00:29:07.720
which is below the Gambia River,

00:29:07.720 --> 00:29:12.020
and also some of the coastal areas
were places were other full spike

00:29:12.020 --> 00:29:14.090
lute traditions existed.

00:29:14.090 --> 00:29:15.670
This is John Snipes.

00:29:15.670 --> 00:29:18.870
He was the first black banjo
player that I ever met.

00:29:18.870 --> 00:29:25.820
He lived in Dobson Crossroads near
Chapel Hill in a cabin, log cabin,

00:29:25.820 --> 00:29:29.050
with his wife, and his
grandchildren were there often.

00:29:29.050 --> 00:29:32.170
He's playing the "Coo
Coo," the same song

00:29:32.170 --> 00:29:35.510
that you heard Tom Ashley
play, but how different.

00:29:35.510 --> 00:29:41.070
[ Music ]

00:29:41.070 --> 00:29:45.880
And notice that the banjo songs
are built on little rifts.

00:29:45.880 --> 00:29:47.940
I mean, we use that word with jazz,

00:29:47.940 --> 00:29:51.510
but this was a much older
tradition that influenced it.

00:29:51.510 --> 00:30:01.210
[ Music ]

00:30:01.210 --> 00:30:04.890
Another great one he played
