00:30:26.680 --> 00:30:30.310
because he ran all night
and the sun was rising.

00:30:30.310 --> 00:30:33.410
Okay. But again, we
were wrong to think

00:30:33.410 --> 00:30:35.370
that the griot lutes
were the first ones

00:30:35.370 --> 00:30:39.050 position:56%
because form is the most persistent,

00:30:39.050 --> 00:30:43.420
beyond construction
and beyond function.

00:30:43.420 --> 00:30:50.810
And notice, this is Daniel Jatta,
whom I was just telling you about,

00:30:50.810 --> 00:30:54.980
he's playing the full spike lute,
the akonting, the folk lute,

00:30:54.980 --> 00:30:58.920
not the griot professionalized
instrument,

00:30:58.920 --> 00:31:02.350
and behind him is a Boucher banjo,

00:31:02.350 --> 00:31:07.520
which was one of the most
famous first banjo makers.

00:31:07.520 --> 00:31:10.930
And notice how similar from
the front the shapes are.

00:31:10.930 --> 00:31:14.920
And it's no longer a gourd
after about a hundred years,

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:20.620
but then people well, there
were a couple of white guys

00:31:20.620 --> 00:31:27.810
in the 1830s started playing these
instruments, the gourd instruments,

00:31:27.810 --> 00:31:34.500
and eventually Joel
Sweeney either popularized

00:31:34.500 --> 00:31:40.540
or invented the five-string
banjo, which had five strings.

00:31:40.540 --> 00:31:43.520
The fifth string that was added is
not what we call the fifth string

00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:47.670
with the short string now
that you play with your thumb,

00:31:47.670 --> 00:31:52.830
but it was the fourth long string
that was added that made it a total

00:31:52.830 --> 00:31:57.510
of five strings and it gave
more melodic capability

00:31:57.510 --> 00:32:00.100
to the European styles.

00:32:00.100 --> 00:32:04.630
Just to finish with a story
about Daniel for a second.

00:32:04.630 --> 00:32:09.660
So he was here getting his
MBA and he went home to study

00:32:09.660 --> 00:32:14.070
with his father, who died within
a year, so we're very lucky

00:32:14.070 --> 00:32:16.920
that he did become
interested in that tradition.

00:32:16.920 --> 00:32:19.720
All of his African friends
thought he was crazy,

00:32:19.720 --> 00:32:24.110
why wasn't he making a lot
of money as an economist.

00:32:24.110 --> 00:32:26.260
Well, eventually then
he did go to Sweden

00:32:26.260 --> 00:32:29.660
and become an economist there,
and he started trying to lecture

00:32:29.660 --> 00:32:32.010
about this and people
were not paying attention.

00:32:32.010 --> 00:32:37.210 position:56%
But finally, a banjo player and
lute collector and media specialist,

00:32:37.210 --> 00:32:40.690
Ulf Jagfors, saw how
important what he was saying,

00:32:40.690 --> 00:32:43.370
brought him to this
country in the year 2000

00:32:43.370 --> 00:32:48.390
and revolutionized our
understanding of the banjo.

00:32:48.390 --> 00:32:51.690
So you see how different
the griot lutes are.

00:32:51.690 --> 00:32:56.450
And then this is Jesus Jarju, and
he's playing an akonting also.

00:32:56.450 --> 00:32:58.140
He's from the Jola people.

00:32:58.140 --> 00:33:04.870 position:56%
But notice that it's pear-shaped and
that was an older style instrument.

00:33:04.870 --> 00:33:08.300
I mean, it's the same
concept, it sounded the same,

00:33:08.300 --> 00:33:10.370
but more recently they discovered

00:33:10.370 --> 00:33:14.170
that the round gourd
worked better musically,

00:33:14.170 --> 00:33:16.450
and so that's what almost
all of them are made now.

00:33:16.450 --> 00:33:20.740
But there's the pear-shaped,
the old pear-shaped akonting.

00:33:20.740 --> 00:33:30.500 position:56%
And here's the first painting that
