00:53:28.420 --> 00:53:31.210
&gt;&gt; CeCe Conway: Hammering on is
what we call it, or pulling off.

00:53:31.210 --> 00:53:32.610
Those are techniques.

00:53:32.610 --> 00:53:35.550
Another thing about
Cheick Hamala's playing,

00:53:35.550 --> 00:53:40.740
notice that he was using his
foot taps to set a rhythm,

00:53:40.740 --> 00:53:45.380
and he was also tapping the head
of the ngoni to set a rhythm,

00:53:45.380 --> 00:53:48.900
and those are characteristics
of a lot of black banjo players

00:53:48.900 --> 00:53:52.070
and even a few white players.

00:53:52.070 --> 00:53:58.600
This is a down stroke and there's
a technique called drop thumbing

00:53:58.600 --> 00:54:04.370 position:56%
that's considered what makes a banjo
player more than a backporch picker

00:54:04.370 --> 00:54:07.770
because you not only hit the
drone string but you drop

00:54:07.770 --> 00:54:17.500
down into the melody strings, and
the Jola people use that technique.

00:54:17.500 --> 00:54:21.620
So that's another piece
of evidence of continuity.

00:54:21.620 --> 00:54:26.970
Okay. Here you have a
