missionary who went to Liberia,

00:54:32.830 --> 00:54:34.760
and they're paintings
of older times,

00:54:34.760 --> 00:54:38.980
So you can see the fellow
going up in the palm tree

00:54:38.980 --> 00:54:44.260
and are they trading
with that chip or slaves,

00:54:44.260 --> 00:54:47.430
and slave people being
taken out there.

00:54:47.430 --> 00:54:52.520
This is a painting from 1800s
in South Carolina and notice

00:54:52.520 --> 00:54:55.100 position:56%
that the skit has started to change.

00:54:55.100 --> 00:55:01.370
It has a flat fingerboard and it
has pegs and there are probably --

00:55:01.370 --> 00:55:10.960
most of them designs around the
rim carved, still the gourd head.

00:55:10.960 --> 00:55:15.770 position:56%
And so this came in more
southernly than the earlier pictures

00:55:15.770 --> 00:55:17.680
of the akonting that we have,

00:55:17.680 --> 00:55:22.990 position:56%
and probably through the Caribbean
influence and the Spanish influence.

00:55:22.990 --> 00:55:26.640
Here we've got a black
in minstrel clothes,

00:55:26.640 --> 00:55:31.220
and notice there's an
akonting that he's leaning on.

00:55:31.220 --> 00:55:33.620
Notice this is a minstrel drawing

00:55:33.620 --> 00:55:36.040
and the [inaudible],
of course, the problem.

00:55:36.040 --> 00:55:39.580
We'll get back to that in a minute.

00:55:39.580 --> 00:55:44.340
But notice that the long stick neck
is the full spike akonting there

00:55:44.340 --> 00:55:46.440
before the minstrels shifted

00:55:46.440 --> 00:55:50.930
from the African banjos
to their new open back.

00:55:50.930 --> 00:55:55.470
This is Joel Sweeney, one of the
first white men to learn to play.

00:55:55.470 --> 00:55:59.340
This is a Boucher banjo,
like the one in the painting.

00:55:59.340 --> 00:56:02.970
Here is one of the first
actual Virginia banjos made

00:56:02.970 --> 00:56:04.380
by a cabinetmaker.

00:56:04.380 --> 00:56:06.390
Here you have, again, a mount.

00:56:06.390 --> 00:56:09.830
And then in minstrelsy
it's interesting

00:56:09.830 --> 00:56:13.160
that they began first as dancers.

00:56:13.160 --> 00:56:17.040
And Juba Lane was the only
black in early minstrelsy.

00:56:17.040 --> 00:56:21.770 position:56%
He was described by Charles Dickens,
and he finally went to London

00:56:21.770 --> 00:56:25.780
where he could enjoy
his talent more easily.

00:56:25.780 --> 00:56:29.790
Eventually the banjo became
the center of minstrelsy,

00:56:29.790 --> 00:56:35.470
but here you have a single
banjo player with the dancer.

00:56:35.470 --> 00:56:42.460
There were serious and
frustrating stereotyping during

00:56:42.460 --> 00:56:43.830
that whole period.

00:56:43.830 --> 00:56:48.650
However, in many ways I think
minstrelsy was an attempt

00:56:48.650 --> 00:56:51.820
to address the fact that in it was
the first popular entertainment

00:56:51.820 --> 00:56:58.010
in this country, and in some ways
an attempt to address the new issue

00:56:58.010 --> 00:57:01.230
of black and whites
living close together.

00:57:01.230 --> 00:57:02.840
And had it been more successful,

00:57:02.840 --> 00:57:05.090
maybe we wouldn't have
had the Civil War.

00:57:05.090 --> 00:57:07.280
What did come of interest

00:57:07.280 --> 00:57:11.520
as the instrument makers were
erasing the African roots

00:57:11.520 --> 00:57:17.040
of the banjo, and were beautiful
banjos, the Fairbanks banjos

00:57:17.040 --> 00:57:19.470
of the 1900s are about the best.

00:57:19.470 --> 00:57:21.430 position:56%
Now the African roots of the fiddle.

