for Patrick Henry to dance

00:57:31.330 --> 00:57:34.190
when Jefferson was on
his way to Williamsburg.

00:57:34.190 --> 00:57:35.540
The cittern.

00:57:35.540 --> 00:57:40.060
Jefferson gave the only description
of a tuning for the banjo,

00:57:40.060 --> 00:57:44.770
and he compared it to a guitar,
but it was an English guitar,

00:57:44.770 --> 00:57:47.640
and so it's not the
tunings that we have today.

00:57:47.640 --> 00:57:49.410
And actually, the way
he described it,

00:57:49.410 --> 00:57:51.480
it could have been
one of two tunings.

00:57:51.480 --> 00:57:57.050
Isaac Jefferson was
his ace blacksmith.

00:57:57.050 --> 00:58:00.190
He could make more nails
faster than anybody else.

00:58:00.190 --> 00:58:04.510
And he said how Jefferson's brother
Randolph used to come and dance

00:58:04.510 --> 00:58:06.510
and play the fiddle
with the black folks,

00:58:06.510 --> 00:58:09.000
and he just should
have been more careful.

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:13.280
In Jefferson's own hand he wrote
down the tune "Money Musk",

00:58:13.280 --> 00:58:17.160
and I think Jerome's going to
play that for you a little later.

00:58:17.160 --> 00:58:23.020
And it was also played by Eston
Hemmings, Sally Hemmings' son,

00:58:23.020 --> 00:58:25.720
and possibly Jefferson's.

00:58:25.720 --> 00:58:28.090
There's Modu [phonetic],
the coolest [inaudible]

00:58:28.090 --> 00:58:34.690
of the one-string fiddle,
and other related folks.

00:58:34.690 --> 00:58:38.280
This is the house where Sally
Hemmings lived with her sons

00:58:38.280 --> 00:58:42.700
after Jefferson died that
he had arranged for her.

